<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How is EV range calculated?", answer: "EV range is calculated by dividing the battery capacity (in kWh) by the energy consumption rate (in Wh per mile). A 75 kWh battery with an efficiency of 250 Wh/mile gives a base range of 300 miles. Real-world range is then adjusted for speed, temperature, HVAC use, cargo weight, and driving style, which can reduce range by 10-40% from the EPA rating." },
  { question: "How much does cold weather affect EV range?", answer: "Cold weather can reduce EV range by 20-40%. At 20 degrees Fahrenheit, expect roughly 30% less range than the rated specification. This is caused by reduced battery chemical activity, increased energy needed for cabin heating, and higher rolling resistance from cold tires. Preconditioning the cabin while plugged in helps minimize cold weather range loss." },
  { question: "Does driving speed affect EV range?", answer: "Yes, speed dramatically affects EV range due to aerodynamic drag. At 55 mph, most EVs achieve close to their rated range. At 70 mph, expect 15-20% less range. At 80 mph, range can drop 25-30% or more. This is because aerodynamic drag increases with the square of speed, requiring exponentially more energy at higher speeds." },
  { question: "How long does it take to charge an EV?", answer: "Charging time depends on the charger type. Level 1 (standard outlet, 1.4 kW) takes 40-60 hours for a full charge. Level 2 (home charger, 7-11 kW) takes 6-12 hours. DC Fast Charging (50-350 kW) can add 200 miles of range in 20-40 minutes. Most EV owners charge overnight at home on Level 2, starting each day with a full battery." },
  { question: "What is Wh/mile efficiency and what is good?", answer: "Wh/mile (Watt-hours per mile) measures how much energy an EV uses per mile driven. Lower numbers are better. Efficient small EVs achieve 230-260 Wh/mi, mid-size EVs get 270-300 Wh/mi, and large SUVs and trucks use 350-450 Wh/mi. The EPA rates vehicles in MPGe (miles per gallon equivalent), where 33.7 kWh equals one gallon of gasoline." }
]) %>

